    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/edf09871b6901cb4c562e456d8a06388?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 1296974,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1247781,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1247781/fthompson",
                "reputation": 28807,
                "display_name": "FThompson",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 6,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1344485979,
            "creation_date": 1344485979,
            "body": "<p><code>SOURCE<\/code> annotations are only present in the source file.<\/p>\n\n<p>When the compiler \"discards\" the annotation, it is essentially ignoring that the annotation even exists.  Source annotations basically serve the same purpose as commenting code.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 11876762,
            "question_id": 11876738
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a648ccb47bbbe9497c073315aac4d33e?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 17835,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 40342,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/40342/joachim-sauer",
                "reputation": 309298,
                "display_name": "Joachim Sauer",
                "accept_rate": 62
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1344486032,
            "creation_date": 1344486032,
            "body": "<p>The annotated <em>element<\/em> is not affected.<\/p>\n\n<p><code>@Retention<\/code> is what you'd call a meta-annotation: it <em>only<\/em> applies to <em>other annotation interfaces<\/em>. As such it also <em>only<\/em>  affects the <em>annotation<\/em> it is applied to.<\/p>\n\n<p>For example if you had an annotation named <code>@Foo<\/code> that is <em>itself<\/em> annotated with <code>@Retention(RetentionPolicy.SOURCE)<\/code>, then the <code>@Foo<\/code> annotation (on another element) would be parsed by the compiler, but <em>not<\/em> stored in the resulting <code>.class<\/code> file (so if you'd ask the runtime if the element had the <code>@Foo<\/code> annotation, you'd get a negative answer).<\/p>\n\n<p>This can be useful if you use an annotation purely for documentation purposes or if you want to handle it with annotation processing (during the compile step).<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 11876768,
            "question_id": 11876738
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/mSjyZ.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 1931986,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 3990012,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3990012/serup",
                "reputation": 3906,
                "display_name": "serup",
                "accept_rate": 64
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1442300467,
            "creation_date": 1442300467,
            "body": "<p>In the Java programming language, annotations can be used as a special form of syntactic metadata in the source code.\nClasses, methods, variables, parameters and packages may be annotated. The annotations can be embedded in class files generated by the compiler and may be RETAINED by the Java virtual machine and thus influence the run-time behaviour of an application.<\/p>\n\n<p>A retention policy determines at what point annotation should be discarded.\nAnnotation with retention policy RUNTIME will be available to the JVM through runtime.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 32579688,
            "question_id": 11876738
        }
    ],
